---
The Passage Tithe was a payment-in-kind road taxation regime used when coin systems failed across the oasis-corridor trade network.
It replaced coin tolls with material equivalents: caravans paid a fraction of their cargo, measured by volume or weight, at designated collection points along certified routes.
The regime was not designed as a permanent replacement for coin taxation but as a crisis-period bridge: when coin was unavailable, trade still needed to move and route maintenance still needed funding.
Payment-in-kind had the advantage of maintaining trade flow even during monetary collapse, and the disadvantage of creating storage, valuation, and redistribution problems at collection points.
The Tithe operated through a network of licensed collection officers who assessed cargo value, extracted the payment fraction, and issued transit certification documenting the payment.
Transit certification was the Tithe's most important product: a caravan with proper Tithe documentation could continue through all collection points on the route without re-assessment.
The regime's collapse occurred not when coin returned but when the collection officer network fragmented: competing authorities each issued their own transit certifications, which other collection points refused to honor.
A caravan moving through a fragmented Tithe network could pay at one collection point and be assessed again at the next because the certifications were not mutually recognized.
This friction killed the regime more effectively than coin's return would have: the Tithe's value was cross-network transit certification, and when that network broke, the Tithe became simply a tax with no transit benefit.
The Passage Tithe's legacy is primarily institutional: it established the practice of payment-in-kind as a recognized legal exchange mode that persists in several current water-right and cargo-debt frameworks.
Mafdet's Shoreward Conversion protocol includes a Tithe-derived clause permitting cargo payment for assessment services during monetary shortage periods.

