Midgaard's registry includes the Passage Tithe as a pre-charter legal instrument classified as pre-charter origin but valid; its transit certification documents are accepted as evidence of route use continuity for property rights purposes.
A route documented by Tithe certifications has stronger continuity-of-use evidence than a route without documentation, even if the Tithe certification predates the charter system.
The Continuity faction treats Tithe documentation as the strongest available historical evidence for pre-charter route rights.
The Reckoning faction notes that Tithe documentation was issued by a fragmented system where certification authority was contested; not all Tithe documents reflect legitimate collection.
Both factions agree distinguishing legitimate from contested Tithe documentation requires case-by-case analysis. Neither agrees on who should conduct that analysis.

flags KOWLOON
---
Kowloon's Black Ledger includes the Passage Tithe as the historical precursor to its current cargo-assessment levy system.
What the Tithe got right: payment-in-kind maintains trade flow when coin fails; transit certification creates a cross-network pass that reduces redundant assessment; fraction-of-cargo scales automatically with cargo value.
What the Tithe got wrong: collection network coherence was more fragile than the coin system it replaced; without a single authority backing transit certifications, fragmentation was inevitable.
Kowloon's response: the Neon Covenant's levy system requires all collection points to honor transit certifications issued at any other Kowloon-recognized point — explicitly cited as the lesson drawn from the Tithe's fragmentation failure.
Kowloon's assessment: a correct response to an impossible situation that failed because cross-network trust is harder to maintain than the goods it was meant to move. Building the trust structure before the crisis is the lesson.

flags KIESS
---
Kiess's route law includes a Tithe-derived survival tariff: a certified caravan in documented distress may pay a fraction of cargo rather than coin at any Kiess-licensed collection point.
The survival tariff is not charity: the caravan still pays, the collection point still receives value, and transit certification is issued normally. It is crisis accommodation that preserves route function when the standard payment form is unavailable.
Kiess's anti-secrecy doctrine required full public disclosure of the survival tariff's terms: what distress qualifies, what fractions apply by cargo type, and what documentation the caravan must provide.
Kiess publishes its active mutual recognition agreements quarterly; collection points delisted from recognition are also disclosed with the reason for delisting. This prevents the fragmentation confusion that destroyed the original Tithe network.

