---
Rakuen's disaster-recovery framework treats the Passage Tithe as the historical model for crisis-period resource allocation when monetary systems fail.
Rakuen's modern payment-in-kind option during crisis periods is administered through a central clearing function rather than distributed collection points.
Caravans pay at any point and receive a Rakuen-issued transit certification; Rakuen then redistributes collected cargo to maintenance operations and crisis recovery stores.
This centralization was Rakuen's specific response to the Tithe's fragmentation failure: if certification is issued and backed by a single institution, mutual recognition is automatic.
The tradeoff is that Rakuen bears all redistribution logistics costs. The Garden Ledger notes: the Tithe worked for the caravans. It failed for the route system. Rakuen's version works for the route system. It costs more. The cost is justified because route system failure is more expensive than the clearing operation.

