Mafdet's Shoreward Conversion protocol includes a Tithe-derived clause permitting cargo payment for Shoreward assessment services during documented monetary shortage periods.
The Tide Ledger Hall's Saltweight standard was partly developed in response to the Tithe period's valuation inconsistencies: different collection points assessed cargo value differently, creating conversion disputes at coastal handoff. A universal measurement standard eliminates this dispute.
Mafdet's Claw Mark Registry includes a historical Tithe certification sub-archive: surviving Tithe documents from cargo that eventually reached Mafdet's harbor, allowing provenance chains to be traced back through the Tithe period.
The Shrine of the First Claw notes that the Tithe's fraction-of-cargo model is an ancient form of oath-sealed contribution: you swear to the fraction, you pay it, and you receive transit clearance. The Shrine recognizes the Tithe model as a valid ancestor of current commercial oath forms.

