---
Deltari in Kowloon maintain oral records of the Passage Tithe's operation in the delta region that predate Kowloon's administrative records, documenting how the Tithe functioned for small-boat operators, reed traders, and seasonal fish-cargo routes.
These operators faced different challenges than overland caravans: perishable cargo, shorter routes, fewer payment-in-kind options. A caravan can pay a fraction of grain; a reed boat cannot pay a fraction of fish.
Deltari records document the local adaptation: Tithe collection points near the delta accepted preservation work rather than cargo fraction — salting, drying, and storage services in lieu of cargo.
This service-payment variant was improvised by Deltari collection officers and later acknowledged by Kowloon's administrative records as locally valid; Kowloon's current levy system includes a service-payment option for perishable cargo routes tracing directly to this Deltari adaptation.
The adaptation is acknowledged in Kowloon's documentation. The Deltari origin is not. Deltari in Kowloon's administrative system are working to add the attribution.
